21:<In the classical wave equation derivation (around 5:15 of 'The Classical Wave Equation' video),

    (y_(j+1) - 2y_j + y_(j-1)) / (delta z)^2

is simplified to

    del^2 y / del z^2

Where does this come from? There is no equation that describes `y`, so how do we know what its second partial derivative w.r.t `z` is?

**EDIT**: Ok, I think I've figured it out. This makes a lot more sense if you don't simplify the numerator in the previous step, which was originally:

    [(y_(j+1) - y_j) - (y_j + y_(j-1))]

The numerator is just `[delta y_j - delta y_(j-1)]`, which is `del^2 y`.

No idea why the numerator was simplified...it's so much easier to understand like this :)>
