39:<Normalisation gives dimension to the wavefunction.

In a 1-D infinite well with width $L$, the wavefunction $psi(x)$ is normalised by a factor $A_{1D}propto sqrt{frac{1}{L}}$ so that $|psi_N(x)|^2$ has dimension $[L^{-1}]$ and the integral $int psi_N(x) dx$ is then dimensionless as a probablility should be.

For a 3-D infinite well with volume $L_x L_y L_z$, the wavefunction $psi(x,y,z)=psi(V)$ is normalised by a factor $A_{3D}propto sqrt{frac{1}{L_xL_yL_z}}$ so that $|psi_N(V)|^2$ has dimension $[L^{-3}]$ and the integral $int psi_N(V) dV$ is again dimensionless. 

So the dimension of the **normalised** 3-D wavefunction means that as well as being a probablility amplitude it can also be called a probability density.

The problem in A2Q7 is 1-D so this discussion of probability densities isn't strictly applicable to the question. 

I think the problem expressed by the original poster can be explained when the infinitesimal is applied in the integration of the probability amplitude. The particle is mathematically described as a point (i.e. having no length or volume) and in 1-D we can write the probability of finding the particle in the interval $Delta x$ as

$P(x in Delta x) = int_{Delta x} |psi(x)|^2 dx$

As $Delta x 	o 0$ (but $Delta x 
eq 0$) the interval becomes infinitesimal and therefore cannot be subdivided. Thus $P(x in Delta x) 	o 1$ when $x in Delta x$ and $P(x in Delta x) 	o 0$ otherwise.

The problem alluded to in the original post, that there are multiple $x$ values within the interval $Delta x$ (or within the volume element $Delta V$) which could have different probability amplitudes, does not exist when the limit $Delta x 	o dx$ (or $Delta V 	o dV$) is taken because the interval (or volume) element becomes infinitesimally small. Therefore, to say that $P(x in Delta x)$ is **equal to** 0 or 1 is not quite correct. It only **tends towards** 0 or 1 which then leaves room for an uncertainty principle and also means that it isn't possible to say a particle is present with absolute certainty (i.e. with unitary probability).

I hope this makes some kind of sense and I'll be glad to hear your thoughts.>
