61:<I don't see how $c$ can't be but $1$. Since in Q4 $f(x)=psi_k(x)$ for some $k$, from the definition of expansion coefficients, we have $psi_k(x)=sum_{n} c_n psi_n(x)$. Multiplying both sides by $psi_k^*(x)$, integrating, and assuming orthogonality, we get $c_k=1$.

Note that it suffices to assume linear independence, since rearranging the expansion as $(1-c_k)psi_k(x)=sum_{n
eq k} c_n psi_n(x)$, we then need $1-c_k=0$.>
62:<So, while there's no analytic solution for $sqrt{epsilon}	an(frac{pi}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{epsilon}) = sqrt{
u_0 - epsilon}$ (and the other equation), I got curious whether the *number of solutions* could be found out analytically. The answer turned out to be an easy yes.

![enter image description here][<zipRedac>]


Red curve: $sqrt{
u_0 - epsilon}$, Blue curve(s): $sqrt{epsilon}	an(frac{pi}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{epsilon})$, Yellow curve(s): $-sqrt{epsilon}cot(frac{pi}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{epsilon})$

The number of intersections (solutions) is the number of blue and yellow curve(s) that cut the $x$ axis in the interval $[0, 
u_0]$. 

$sqrt{epsilon}	an(frac{pi}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{epsilon})$ cuts the $x$ axis whenever $frac{pi}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{epsilon} = (n - 1)pi$. Since the maximum value of $epsilon$ is  $
u_0$, we get the number of solutions, $n le 1 + frac{1}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{
u_0} = leftlfloor 1 + frac{1}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{
u_0} ightfloor$. 

A similar reasoning for $-sqrt{epsilon}cot(frac{pi}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{epsilon})$, yields the number of solutions $m = leftlfloor frac{1}{<zipRedac>} + frac{1}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{
u_0} ightfloor$

So, the total number of solutions, and thus eigenstates, is $N = n + m = leftlfloor 1 + frac{1}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{
u_0} ightfloor + leftlfloor frac{1}{<zipRedac>} + frac{1}{<zipRedac>}sqrt{
u_0} ightfloor approx 1 + sqrt{
u_0}$ to the nearest integer.


For example, $
u_0 = 40$ (in the graph above), gives $N = lfloor 4.16 floor + lfloor 3.66 floor = 7$.

We can substitute $
u_0 = V_0 / E_1^{infty}$ to get $N approx 1 + sqrt{<zipRedac>mV_0}L_z/hbar pi$

Some fun this was :)

  [1]: https://edx-west-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com/<phoneRedac><zipRedac>08946.png
  [<zipRedac>]: https://edx-west-uploads.s3.amazonaws.com/<phoneRedac><zipRedac>9<zipRedac>679.png>
63:<But note that, from my reasoning above, *whatever* the basis set including non-normalized $psi(x)=x$ is, its expansion coefficient $c$ can't be computed according to the definition given in the quiz, because if you do, you can't "complete" $f(x)=x$ with the other functions in the basis, since they are (supposed to be) orthogonal (or at least linearly independent) with respect to $f(x)=psi(x)$. So, as I see it, if $c$ is the expansion coefficient for $psi$, it can only be $1$. So, the definition of $c$ in the quiz only applies to normalized $psi$, which is not the case.>
64:<Thank you very much for the explanation! 

As I understand, your boundary conditions to discard a left-moving wave on the right side are that it can't be physically generated, since there is no second barrier to the right. 

I still don't understand well how do the probabilities apply, in particular if the wave corresponds to the probability amplitude of a single electron and I wanted to detect it by putting a plate on the left side far from the barrier, and also at a very long distance from its source (which I suppose much farther to the left). What would be the probabilities to detect it on *each* side of the plate? I suppose it can only depend on *when* I put the plate. If it's soon, it's hard to imagine that it can't be but $p=1$, on the left side of the plate (i.e. only consider the first wave, normalized). If we let the electron pass by, and then put the plate, consider only the other two scattered waves, re-normalized.

Now, if instead of a single electron it's a wave plenty of them, I suppose that for that same plate and position, I'd had to compute the probabilities from the normalized 3-component wave equation. In principle, with probability $p_1$ of detecting electrons on the left side of the plate greater than $p_2$ on its right side, with $p_3=1-p_1-p_2$ corresponding to "lost" electrons that passed the original barrier. I'd even say that $p_1$ should be about $0.5$, since there are "as many" electrons on both sides of the plate. In summary, we should have $p_1=p_2+p_3=0.5$.

But all that reasoning seems hard to reconcile in both cases, particularly in the latter, with the computed wavefunction: it's hard to admit that if I put the plate precisely in one (of many such) point where $|psi|^2$ is 0, I'll detect no electron: where would they go? The only way out I can imagine is that when we'll consider time later on in the course, integration on time will give us sort of the probabilities as above, and that currently the wavefunctions can be only considered as in, say, $t=0$ or, more generally, $t=kT$. However, that'd be conceptually different from the infinite potential well, where I understood that the solution waves were stationary.>
