80:<Just to comment that the expression "energy at the bottom" was confusing for me. 

Since it's the electron that has the energy (there is no "bottom" in the "well", which is just a region where the electron is confined; and there isn't, or at least we haven't been taught of, energy "at a place"), one may reasonably think that it means the "lowest possible energy" (at the "bottom" of the possible energy levels for the electron). Moreover, this interpretation is in fact quite in accordance with the lecture where this energy was given a specific name ("zero-point energy"), which again seems to be quite equivalent to "energy at the bottom". Finally, the phrase, if interpreted as in the answer, is in itself unnecessary (and so its presence confusing), it had sufficed in that case to ask for the expected energy, i.e. absolute one.

