112:<For this question there is no need to "make a Hamiltonian". But you should know the Hamiltonian for a simple particle in a potential, which I am pretty sure has been discussed before in this course: $H=p^2/2m+V(x)$, which on substituting the operator representation for p: p=?i?d/dx, leads directly to the Schrodinger equation.

