134:<moonlove,

Please disregard the nasty noobie-biting above.  The straightforward answer would be "no".  But, you can still review the materials and learn from them though.  Do it!  It's great! :-)

The way it works is that you can get points if you do the "quizes" (which for *this* course are akin to homework) and "assignments" (which for this course are like tests) before the due date (actually "due moment").  After that moment, the answers may be discussed openly and the correct answers are displayed right there below the question.  So, no points can be awarded for "correct" answers then because the answers are already given.

If you start in the middle of the course, you've lost the opportunity to get the points from the first part of the course.  After about a few weeks into the course, you won't be able to get a certificate even if you score 100% on the rest of the course.  Depending on your personality, you may or may not need that certificate/grade incentive to compel you learn the material thoroughly.  Most people need that incentive, I know **I** need it.  If you're superhuman though, then maybe you don't.

But, regardless of how deeply you learn it, you *will* learn *something* good!  So, do it.  The world needs *you* to understand QM.  The more the world knows QM, the faster technology moves, and the sooner I get my flying car!  :-)>
