158:<It's not even necessary to memorize that mysterious equation.  This one can be "derived on the fly" in a moment.  You just have to know that r*exp(i*theta), or the result of *any* equation, is a complex number, a point on the complex plane.  Complex numbers are both 1) "two-dimensional" numbers and 2) a complete general definition of the *idea* of a "number".  r*exp(i*theta) in the complex plane compares to the polar form of plotting a point (a 2D number) on the XY plane.  At the same time, the a+b*i form in the complex plane compares to the "rectangular" form of plotting a point on the XY plane.

Often (as it is here) r is 1.0, so "exp(i*theta)" is a point in the complex plane on a unit circle.  It's at an angle "theta" counterclockwise from the real axis just like polar coordinates.  From that,the "X" component (a) must be cos(theta) and the "Y" component (b) must be sin(theta).  To get the "a+b*i" form, the "vertical" component of that two-dimensional number (complex number) plane is written as multiplied by "i".  So it falls out that the result is cos(theta) + i*sin(theta)

That's one less weirdo identity the human race needs to remember!  :-)>
