172:<Actually other terms is not all zero :)
I tried by integral and that's what I get :
*the diagonal elements are i*i
*the element where i+j= even is all zero (because of symmetry)
*the elements over the diagonal (j=i+1) and (i=j+1) are following the empirical result you opposed ;)
*the elements with (i=j+3) or (j=i+3) (Away off the diagonal) also exist and following the same empirical relation but by multiplying by 1/9 = 3^-2 
*the elements with (i=j+5) or (j=i+5) (Far away off the diagonal) also exist and following the same empirical relation but by multiplying by 1/25 = 5^-2 
*the elements with (i=j+7) or (j=i+7) (Very far away off the diagonal) also exist and following the same empirical relation but by multiplying by 1/49 = 7^-2
*the elements with (i=j+9) or (j=i+9) (Very very far away off the diagonal) also exist and following the same empirical relation but by multiplying by 1/81 = 9^-2
.
